 {"id":"remote_compilation_helper-a4q","title":"Telemetry and SpeedScore Persistent Storage Layer","description":"## Overview
Implement the persistent storage layer for telemetry snapshots and SpeedScore history, enabling the dashboard to display historical data and enabling data survival across daemon restarts.

## Background and Justification
Current telemetry design (bead 1aq) describes in-memory storage with 5-minute retention. This is insufficient for:
- Dashboard historical charts (need 30+ days of data)
- SpeedScore trend analysis
- Post-mortem debugging
- Daemon restart recovery

## Storage Requirements

### Telemetry Data
- **Volume**: ~20 samples/minute × 60 minutes × 24 hours × 30 days = ~864,000 samples per worker
- **Retention**: Configurable, default 30 days for raw data, 1 year for hourly aggregates
- **Access patterns**: Recent data accessed frequently, historical data accessed rarely

### SpeedScore Data
- **Volume**: ~4 benchmarks/day × 365 days = ~1,460 records per worker per year
- **Retention**: Indefinite (small volume)
- **Access patterns**: Latest score accessed constantly, history accessed on-demand

## Implementation: SQLite with WAL Mode

### Why SQLite
- No external dependencies (embedded)
- Excellent performance for this workload
- Built-in WAL mode for concurrent reads during writes
- Single-file deployment simplicity

### Schema

\`\`\`sql
-- Telemetry snapshots (high-volume, time-series data)
CREATE TABLE telemetry_snapshots (
    id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,
    worker_id TEXT NOT NULL,
    timestamp INTEGER NOT NULL,  -- Unix timestamp (seconds)

    -- CPU metrics
    cpu_percent REAL NOT NULL,
    cpu_user_percent REAL,
    cpu_system_percent REAL,
    cpu_iowait_percent REAL,
    load_avg_1m REAL,
    load_avg_5m REAL,
    load_avg_15m REAL,

    -- Memory metrics
    memory_total_mb INTEGER,
    memory_available_mb INTEGER,
    memory_used_percent REAL,
    swap_used_percent REAL,

    -- Disk metrics
    disk_read_mbps REAL,
    disk_write_mbps REAL,
    disk_iops REAL,
    disk_utilization_percent REAL,

    -- Network metrics
    network_rx_mbps REAL,
    network_tx_mbps REAL,
    network_error_rate REAL
);

-- Indexes for common queries
CREATE INDEX idx_telemetry_worker_time ON telemetry_snapshots(worker_id, timestamp DESC);
CREATE INDEX idx_telemetry_time ON telemetry_snapshots(timestamp);

-- Hourly aggregates (for long-term storage efficiency)
CREATE TABLE telemetry_hourly (
    worker_id TEXT NOT NULL,
    hour_timestamp INTEGER NOT NULL,  -- Unix timestamp (hour boundary)
    sample_count INTEGER NOT NULL,

    -- Aggregated metrics (avg, min, max)
    cpu_percent_avg REAL,
    cpu_percent_max REAL,
    memory_used_percent_avg REAL,
    disk_utilization_avg REAL,

    PRIMARY KEY (worker_id, hour_timestamp)
);

-- SpeedScore history
CREATE TABLE speedscore_history (
    id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,
    worker_id TEXT NOT NULL,
    measured_at INTEGER NOT NULL,  -- Unix timestamp

    -- Scores (0-100 scale)
    total_score REAL NOT NULL,
    cpu_score REAL NOT NULL,
    memory_score REAL NOT NULL,
    disk_score REAL NOT NULL,
    network_score REAL NOT NULL,
    compilation_score REAL NOT NULL,

    -- Raw benchmark results (JSON blob for flexibility)
    raw_results TEXT,

    -- Version for algorithm changes
    algorithm_version INTEGER NOT NULL DEFAULT 1
);

CREATE INDEX idx_speedscore_worker_time ON speedscore_history(worker_id, measured_at DESC);

-- Latest SpeedScore per worker (materialized for fast access)
CREATE TABLE speedscore_latest (
    worker_id TEXT PRIMARY KEY,
    speedscore_id INTEGER NOT NULL REFERENCES speedscore_history(id),
    total_score REAL NOT NULL,  -- Denormalized for fast queries
    measured_at INTEGER NOT NULL
);
